  "prompt": "What happens to your phlegm after swallowing it?",
  "response": "When you swallow phlegm, it typically travels down your esophagus and into your stomach. Once it reaches the stomach, the acidic environment and digestive enzymes work to break it down. The mucus component is digested along with other contents in the stomach. Any pathogens or particulate matter trapped in the phlegm are neutralized by the stomach acid.\n\nAfter digestion in the stomach, the remaining contents move into the intestines, where they are further processed and absorbed. Waste products eventually pass through the large intestine and are excreted from the body.",
